    Systematic review with meta-analysis: the accuracy of serological tests to support the diagnosis of coeliac disease.
Anti-tissue transglutaminase sensitivity appears to be sufficient to rule out coeliac disease in children. The high specificity of endomysial antibody in adults supports its use to rule in coeliac disease. This evidence underpins the current development of clinical guidelines for a serological diagnosis of coeliac disease. Studies in primary care are needed to evaluate serological testing strategies in this setting.
Pubmed   Journal   ReadQx 
J Hepatol
    Systematic review of response criteria and endpoints in autoimmune hepatitis by the International Autoimmune Hepatitis Group.
The need for agreed endpoints is urgently required to set a general standard for reporting study results and make results comparable in future clinical trials. Therefore, the International Autoimmune Hepatitis Group (IAIHG) here presents a statement on five agreed response criteria and endpoints: complete biochemical response, insufficient response, non-response, remission, and intolerance to treatment.
